At the interface plane, the p-SMAC is characterized by an LFA-1–immunoreactive ring (Figs. 7–9
) surrounding a central area of increased TCR immunoreactivity (Figs. 7–9
) and low or absent LFA-1 (Figs. 7, 8, and 10). Note that in most cases LFA-1 immunoreactivity increases within the p-SMAC (Fig. 10, D, G, and I), whereas in others there is a drop in c-SMAC LFA-1 (Fig. 10, F, H, and E); both distributions provide a p-SMAC–rich/c-SMAC–poor LFA-1 pattern. Finally, in those T cells forming mature immunological synapses, we observed that T cells' nuclei displayed a polarized notch open toward the immunological synapse, indicating that the whole structure of T cells polarized toward the immunological synapse (Fig. 8, A and E).
